ABOUT

*VoroTop* is a modern set of open-source tools for analyzing structure of spatial point sets in three dimensions, using a complete description of the Voronoi cell topology of each point. The power of this approach results from its coarse-graining of structural data in a natural configuration space, instead of in the image of this space under a continuous mapping, which has notable theoretical restrictions. More information about the method can be found in the papers:

Lazar, E.A., Han, J., and Srolovitz, D.J. "A Topological Framework for Local Structure Analysis in Condensed Matter", http://arxiv.org/abs/1508.05937, Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. 112:E5769 (2015).

Landweber, P.S., Lazar, E.A., Patel, N. "On Fiber Diameters of Continuous Maps", http://arxiv.org/abs/1503.07597, Amer. Math. Monthly 123:392 (2016).

Lazar, E.A., Lu, J., and Rycroft, C.H., "Voronoi cell analysis: The shapes of particle systems", https://arxiv.org/abs/2201.10842, Am. J. Phys. 90:469 (2022). 

Lazar, E.A., Lu, J., Rycroft, C.H., and Schwarcz, D., "Characterizing structural features of two-dimensional particle systems through Voronoi topology", https://arxiv.org/abs/2406.00553, Model. Simul. Mater. Sci. Eng. 32:085022 (2024). 
